00:41:00,862 --> 00:41:03,624
This is a common aphorism, particularly amongst games journalists.

841
00:41:03,644 --> 00:41:06,106
Games journalists love to say this, I used to be one,

842
00:41:06,606 --> 00:41:09,188
because when you're a games journalist, your job is to analyze a game

843
00:41:09,228 --> 00:41:10,909
and say why it's good and why it's bad.

844
00:41:11,290 --> 00:41:15,352
And if you notice some subtle little thing in Legend of Zelda or Half-Life 2

845
00:41:15,392 --> 00:41:15,593
that...

846
00:41:17,774 --> 00:41:21,215
you love, then it's really easy to massively inflate its importance because

847
00:41:21,455 --> 00:41:26,236
A. It was something you noticed and you felt good for noticing it, but also B.

848
00:41:26,256 --> 00:41:28,417
You want to seem slightly more insightful than everyone else and like,

849
00:41:28,637 --> 00:41:31,618
ah, I noticed the subtle thing and I think that's so fucking important. If you didn't

850
00:41:31,638 --> 00:41:35,479
notice that, you don't appreciate the game as well as I do. And for me it was

851
00:41:35,499 --> 00:41:37,379
like, there's a moment in Half-Life 2 when...

852
00:41:39,060 --> 00:41:43,702
Barney throws you your crowbar and this is you know the iconic weapon and

853
00:41:44,182 --> 00:41:46,583
you're going to use it for the rest of the game

