00:46:00,817 --> 00:46:01,957
Nothing has gone wrong, really.

938
00:46:03,117 --> 00:46:08,140
what has happened is the new information is a shame it's bad news for us but it's

939
00:46:08,180 --> 00:46:10,662
nobody's fault it's not a problem someone's created it's the thing that

940
00:46:10,702 --> 00:46:13,764
we've just learned about the task that we're undertaking and now it's my job as

941
00:46:13,784 --> 00:46:18,867
a designer to or as a producer depending on how you want to classify it to decide

942
00:46:19,147 --> 00:46:21,728
do we still want to do that is that feature still worth doing do we have to

943
00:46:21,768 --> 00:46:26,131
do it if we do have to do it is there an easier way to do it can we rethink and

944
00:46:26,171 --> 00:46:29,293
if the answer to all those questions is no and we do have to do it then

945
00:46:30,033 --> 00:46:34,494
I just have to figure out how we fit that all into the schedule and what else we're going to cut

946
00:46:35,634 --> 00:46:37,195
how we figure out how to do that.

947
00:46:37,795 --> 00:46:41,456
And so, it took me an embarrassingly long time to apply that logic to myself

948
00:46:41,616 --> 00:46:45,497
and realize that when I fail to complete something by a massive degree

949
00:46:45,897 --> 00:46:47,858
I should be nicer to myself about it. I should say,

950
00:46:47,898 --> 00:46:51,279
okay, you put in the hours, you tried it, you got more information

951
00:46:51,719 --> 00:46:53,680
this is useful stuff, I've done my job.

952
00:46:54,440 --> 00:46:56,181
So if you are your own boss, be a good one.

953
00:46:56,941 --> 00:47:02,143
And obviously I realize that this is a luxury in my case.

954
00:47:02,163 --> 00:47:03,804
You know, it's been great to be my own boss

955
00:47:03,864 --> 00:47:06,865
and to be in control of my own, how I am treated and stuff.

956
00:47:08,186 --> 00:47:12,568
And obviously I'm also, I'm gonna talk a bit about

957
00:47:13,688 --> 00:47:15,929
how many hours you work and that kind of stuff.

958
00:47:17,050 --> 00:47:19,931
But I want to be very clear that I appreciate

959
00:47:20,011 --> 00:47:21,492
it's a luxury for me to be able to decide

960
00:47:21,512 --> 00:47:22,332
how many hours I want to work.

961
00:47:23,153 --> 00:47:23,673
I work like.

962
00:47:24,120 --> 00:47:25,180
eight hours in a day or something.

963
00:47:26,560 --> 00:47:28,541
And I know that some of you probably work for,

964
00:47:29,041 --> 00:47:30,561
in an environment where you don't get to decide

965
00:47:30,581 --> 00:47:33,201
how much you work, and probably many of you

966
00:47:33,301 --> 00:47:34,622
are sometimes asked to crunch,

967
00:47:35,162 --> 00:47:36,542
and probably many of you don't want to crunch,

968
00:47:36,922 --> 00:47:39,963
and probably many of you are just in a situation

969
00:47:39,983 --> 00:47:41,663
where that is inescapable.

970
00:47:42,423 --> 00:47:44,864
And that's okay, but if anyone is trying

971
00:47:44,904 --> 00:47:46,504
to make you feel personally bad

972
00:47:46,624 --> 00:47:47,764
for not getting the thing done,

973
00:47:47,784 --> 00:47:49,925
if anyone's trying to make you feel like it's your fault

974
00:47:50,025 --> 00:47:52,165
that this job turns out to be a bigger job than you thought,

975
00:47:52,465 --> 00:47:53,265
then fuck that person.

976
00:47:54,093 --> 00:47:55,334
And if it's you, fuck yourself.

977
00:47:59,677 --> 00:48:01,518
So at the end of the day, I just ask myself two questions.

978
00:48:01,558 --> 00:48:04,480
I ask, did I work eight hours and did I work efficiently?

979
00:48:05,961 --> 00:48:08,383
And the number of hours, you can plug your own number in there.

980
00:48:08,523 --> 00:48:10,585
Some people work a lot more than that, some people work less.

981
00:48:11,966 --> 00:48:12,906
Probably most people work more.

982
00:48:14,087 --> 00:48:16,709
And that's not necessarily, like, unhealthy.

983
00:48:17,710 --> 00:48:20,091
Some people just like to work, you know, 12, 14 hours in a day.

984
00:48:20,692 --> 00:48:24,915
I actually, I do do that if I'm really just on a particular problem that's obsessing me

985
00:48:24,955 --> 00:48:27,697
and that I'm really kind of engrossed in and I want to spend that time.

986
00:48:29,038 --> 00:48:31,740
But it's worth kind of setting a standard for yourself, just deciding for yourself,

987
00:48:31,780 --> 00:48:33,741
what is a good workday, what should I be doing every day?

988
00:48:35,162 --> 00:48:38,324
And that applies even if you are working in an office job where it's 9 to 5

989
00:48:38,604 --> 00:48:39,705
and your hours are imposed by someone else.

990
00:48:40,085 --> 00:48:42,667
There's still a difference between showing up for eight hours

991
00:48:42,707 --> 00:48:44,228
and actually working for eight hours, right?

992
00:48:44,929 --> 00:48:46,049
And if you...

993
00:48:46,945 --> 00:48:51,452
didn't work those 8 hours and the reason was you're on Twitter, then you can feel bad about that.

994
00:48:52,874 --> 00:48:56,158
And if you didn't work 8 hours for some like, you know...

995
00:48:57,074 --> 00:48:59,396
family reason or you were ill or something,

996
00:48:59,596 --> 00:49:01,177
then obviously you don't feel bad about that.

997
00:49:01,317 --> 00:49:03,719
That's just something that you just need to ask the question,

998
00:49:03,900 --> 00:49:05,661
find out if you didn't work eight hours, why was it?

999
00:49:06,022 --> 00:49:07,843
And then decide, do I need to do something about that?

1000
00:49:08,083 --> 00:49:09,805
If you didn't work eight hours because you got distracted,

1001
00:49:10,125 --> 00:49:11,306
you do need to do something about that.

1002
00:49:11,326 --> 00:49:12,447
You need to change your working process,

1003
00:49:12,467 --> 00:49:14,229
you need to change your access to distractions,

1004
00:49:14,269 --> 00:49:15,530
you need to change something.

1005
00:49:15,990 --> 00:49:17,552
And the same for the efficiency question.

1006
00:49:17,852 --> 00:49:18,553
Did I work efficiently?

1007
00:49:19,566 --> 00:49:21,086
because it's okay if you didn't get the job done,

1008
00:49:21,527 --> 00:49:22,667
but if the reason you didn't get the job done

1009
00:49:22,707 --> 00:49:24,107
is because you worked in some stupid way,

1010
00:49:24,127 --> 00:49:25,648
you just bashed your head against one tiny problem

1011
00:49:25,668 --> 00:49:26,728
without looking at the bigger picture,

1012
00:49:27,128 --> 00:49:28,108
then you need to ask yourself,

1013
00:49:28,529 --> 00:49:30,109
is there something I can do to avoid that in future?

1014
00:49:30,289 --> 00:49:31,789
That needs something to change.

1015
00:49:32,450 --> 00:49:35,351
Whereas in the example earlier with the elevators,

1016
00:49:35,391 --> 00:49:37,811
I think I said, if that thing is taking, you know,

1017
00:49:38,051 --> 00:49:38,992
10 times longer than you thought,

1018
00:49:39,612 --> 00:49:42,493
then that's not the answer to either of these questions.

1019
00:49:42,953 --> 00:49:43,393
You don't care.

1020
00:49:43,793 --> 00:49:45,153
You worked eight hours, you worked efficiently,

1021
00:49:45,393 --> 00:49:46,274
that's all you have to ask yourself.

1022
00:49:46,654 --> 00:49:47,354
You should feel good about it.

1023
00:49:49,883 --> 00:49:53,385
So to recap, first point was choose ideas

1024
00:49:53,425 --> 00:49:54,686
based on value divided by work,

1025
00:49:54,826 --> 00:49:56,007
i.e. choose efficient ideas.

1026
00:49:56,247 --> 00:49:57,508
Those are more important than good ideas.

1027
00:49:58,329 --> 00:50:00,170
Second one was that quick ideas are worth making.

1028
00:50:00,610 --> 00:50:02,292
Good ideas are worth trying.

1029
00:50:02,452 --> 00:50:05,234
If you're uncertain about how good they'll be,

1030
00:50:05,354 --> 00:50:05,754
just make them.

1031
00:50:06,094 --> 00:50:07,855
If you're uncertain about how long they'll take,

1032
00:50:08,136 --> 00:50:09,997
try making them, just to give it a go

1033
00:50:10,077 --> 00:50:11,398
for a certain limited period of time.

1034
00:50:11,818 --> 00:50:12,979
Do a kind of feasibility study

1035
00:50:13,920 --> 00:50:15,361
and then decide whether to carry on with it.

1036
00:50:16,110 --> 00:50:19,631
Number three is not doing things is instant and free, and it always works.

1037
00:50:20,412 --> 00:50:22,212
So it's always worth considering not doing something.

1038
00:50:23,953 --> 00:50:26,914
Number four, overcome perfectionism by knowing how much is broken.

1039
00:50:28,535 --> 00:50:30,996
Stop polishing the silverware by realizing how much of the house is on fire.

1040
00:50:31,997 --> 00:50:34,578
And number five is if you put in the hours, never feel bad about yourself.

1041
00:50:36,509 --> 00:50:39,091
So I think this stuff is important because your life is precious.

1042
00:50:40,712 --> 00:50:42,413
I think it's okay to waste it making video games

1043
00:50:43,454 --> 00:50:46,277
but it's a shame to spend a lot of it on things that go unappreciated.

1044
00:50:47,718 --> 00:50:48,679
So that's it, thank you very much.

